         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">21/8/65 ¶  ¶ Your letter of the 26 June, dear Mr Bentham, has reached me in due time. ¶  I am wondering and amazed, how you are able to carry so much work on within so short a time, even though I assu...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">65.08.21</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, ff. 172-3.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">21/8/65</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your letter of the 26 June, dear Mr Bentham, has reached me in due time.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> I am wondering and amazed, how you are able to carry so much work on within so short a time, even though I assume, that you have but little interruption. Here as Director of a very large Department with multifarious duties I have at all times but little leisure for descriptive Botany, and as my spirit is half broken I cannot muster courage to work regularly often through the evenings or on the whole Sundays as before. However to proceed to the special them[o]s of my letter. I send herewith the only specimen of an apparently new <name key="Viscum">Viscum</name> I have just received,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Presumably <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Viscum">Viscum</name> orientale</seg>; see Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3, p. 396.</p>
               </note> assuming that you will include the <name key="Loranthaceae">Loranthaceae</name> in the 3. vol. How they can be regarded by any one monochlamydeous is an enigma to me and if the interpretation is given to the parts of <name key="Viscum">Viscum</name>, which I employed in the manuscripts at Kew,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Manuscripts not found.</p>
               </note> you will find that the genus well agrees with <name key="Loranthus">Loranthus</name>, in which the floral parts are receiving more readily their due value. The calyx of some Loranthi of Australia is especially manifest.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It seems Dr Hooker is acquainted with several genera, which ought to have been inserted in the 2 and 1. vol of the flor. Austr. <name key="Bryophyllum">Bryophyllum</name> I mentioned before.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to G. Bentham, 24 December 1864.</p>
               </note> If you refer to the list if Indo-Australian plants in the preface of the flor. Tasm, you will notice as mentioned: <name key="Sandoricum%20Indicum">Sandoricum Indicum</name>, <name key="Sandoricum%20nervosum">Sandoricum nervosum</name>, <name key="Laguncularia%20coccinea">Laguncularia coccinea</name> (this genus is even noted by RBrown in the appendix to Flinders) — In Endlichers Atakta is a plate of <name key="Anamirta%20Baueriana">Anamirta Baueriana</name> without letterpress.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker (1865-60), pp. xlii-xlix; R. Brown (1814), p. 16; Endlicher (1833a), plates 39, 40.</p>
               </note> It is not an Norfolk Island plant and therefore perhaps Australian; if so it is omitted</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr Moore writes to me to day and desires, that in the publication of his plants from the Tweed the name of Mr W. Carron should be mentioned along with his own as that of the collector.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was well aware that Smiths <name key="Metrosideros%20floribunda">Metrosideros floribunda</name> is an <name key="Angophora">Angophora</name> but his name, <name key="Eugenia%20elliptica">Eugenia elliptica</name>, would stand for <name key="Acmena">Acmena</name>. I suppose you noted what I said on the subject in the fragmenta.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B64.02.01, pp. 58-9.</p>
               </note> I fully agree with you, that the untenable genera, with which Berg has burdened the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name>, should be abolished.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>O. Berg (1857-9).</p>
               </note> Great difficulty will arise in limiting the genera of <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name>, which D.C. and others have far too much multiplied.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A. P. de Candolle (1836), A. P. de Candolle (1837) and A. P. de Candolle (1838).</p>
               </note> The <name key="Myrtus">Myrtus</name> of the section <name key="Rhodomyrtus">Rhodomyrtus</name> sent by Hill I have forwarded to you as <name key="Myrtus%20Cuttsiae">Myrtus Cuttsiae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Name not found; it was not cited as an herbarium name in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>How <name key="Rhodamnia">Rhodamnia</name> &amp; <name key="Rhodomyrtus">Rhodomyrtus</name> are to be kept up, without also admitting most of Bergs genera I cannot see.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Among baccate <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> of Australia I admit after a careful examen of all the species here indigenous only <name key="Myrtus">Myrtus</name> and Eugenia. Artificial genera are a great plague &amp; render the view over the members of an order very disturbed. I should be glad to have your opinion concerning <name key="Eugenia%20Wilsoni">Eugenia Wilsoni</name>.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M named <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eugenia%20Wilsoni">Eugenia Wilsoni</name>i</seg> in B65.04.01, p. 2. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3, p. 285 accepted it without comment.</p>
               </note> I trust the supplemental <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> sent to you will reach you before your printing of the 3 vol. begins. Would it not be well to give with this volume a good map of Australia? The one sent to Sir Will Hooker is nearly complete.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to G. Bentham, 24 June 1863.</p>
               </note> There is also a beautiful map published lately by Prof. Petermann, on a small scale. It is most excellent &amp; perhaps he would allow it to be copied, or furnish for a trifle the needful number of copies.<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No map was included: see G. Bentham to M, 19 November 1865; G. Bentham to M, 19 April 1866 (in this edition as 66-04-19b); and M to G. Bentham, 24 January 1866 (in this edition as 66-01-24a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The <name key="Trichosanthes">Trichosanthes</name> now transmitted seems new. It is all I have.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Probably <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Trichosanthes">Trichosanthes</name> hearnii</seg>, named, using M’s herbarium name, in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3, p. 315.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr Hill has sent me one single seed of <name key="Streptosia%20Hillii">Streptosia Hillii</name>, which proves the genus very distinct from <name key="Kennedya">Kennedya</name>.<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M's suggested name <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Streptosia</seg> was not used; Bentham recognised it as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Strongyldon ruber</seg>, see G. Bentham to M, 18 October 1865.</p>
               </note> I did not like to dissect this single seed &amp; send it to you.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Trusting that you will enjoy good health in the prosecution of your labours I remain your </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">regardful </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Mr Hill says that the pod of Streptosia is 2-or 3- seeded</p>
